; COMMENTS
; Lockheed C-130 "Hercules" NATO Transport Aircraft
; Standard tactical transport HF communication configuration
; Widely used by NATO forces for tactical and strategic airlift
;
; Aircraft specifications:
; - Length: 29.8m
; - Wingspan: 40.4m  
; - Cruise altitude: 7,600m (25,000 ft)
; - High-wing design provides excellent ground plane
; - Four turboprop engines (T56 series)
; - Crew: 3-5 plus loadmaster
;
; HF Antenna Systems:
; - Primary: 120m trailing wire antenna
; - Secondary: Fuselage-mounted blade antenna  
; - Wing-tip coupling elements
; - Operating range: 2-30 MHz
; - NATO standard equipment fit
;
; NATO HF Radio Equipment:
; - AN/ARC-190: HF transceiver (2-30 MHz)
; - RT-1556/ARC: Tactical HF radio
; - Harris RF-7800H series (modern variants)
; - SINCGARS compatibility on some variants
;
; Operational Role:
; - Tactical airlift and supply
; - Strategic transport missions
; - Humanitarian operations
; - Special operations support
; - Aerial refueling (KC-130 variants)
;
; HF Communication Requirements:
; - Long-range coordination with airlift control
; - Communication with ground forces
; - En-route position reporting
; - Emergency communication backup
; - Inter-aircraft coordination
;
; NATO vs Soviet Comparison:
; - Shorter antenna (120m vs 200m) - tactical vs strategic role
; - Higher operating altitude than most transports
; - More standardized equipment across NATO nations
; - Focus on tactical rather than strategic communications
; - Better integration with NATO communication networks
;
; Frequency Bands:
; - NATO military: 2-30 MHz (various allocations)
; - International aviation: 2.850-28.000 MHz
; - Emergency: 121.5 MHz (Guard frequency)
; - SATCOM: L-band, UHF satellite (modern variants)
;
; Performance Characteristics:
; - 120m wire â‰ˆ 1/2 wave on 40m band (excellent efficiency)
; - High wing provides superior ground plane vs low wing
; - Free space conditions at cruise altitude
; - 500-800 km tactical communication range typical
; - Excellent omnidirectional coverage
;
; Antenna Deployment:
; - Wire deploys after takeoff, retracts before landing
; - Automatic deployment/retraction system
; - Manual emergency deployment capability
; - Blade antenna provides backup if wire system fails
;
; Modern Upgrades:
; - SATCOM capability (Inmarsat, AEHF)
; - Secure HF with frequency hopping
; - Digital HF modes (STANAG 4285, MIL-STD-188)
; - Integration with Link-16 tactical data links
;
; The C-130 represents NATO's workhorse transport with reliable,
; standardized HF communication systems for tactical operations
